            <h3 id="hybrid-journals">Why are hybrid journals also included in QOAM?</h3>
            <p>Author centric, QOAM provides all journals that offer open access publishing. This entails hybrid journals. Some hybrid journals manage to generate a double income by charging both readers (via full library subscriptions) and authors (via full publication fees).<br/>The initiators of QOAM despise this ‘double dipping’ but QOAM is not the instrument to combat this directly. However, if institutions succeed in negotiating journal licenses that end these practices, the license results and more specifically their effect on the publication fees will be mentioned on QOAM’s web site (be it that in most cases one has to log in with their institutional account to see if this applies to one’s institute). For example, SURFmarket succeeded to settle such deals with SAGE and the Royal Society of Chemistry on behalf of UKB, the Dutch consortium of university libraries and the National Library.</p>

            <h3 id="subscription-journals">Why are subscription journals not included in QOAM?</h3>
            <p>QOAM is in the overlap of three domains: (1) Quality, (2) Open Access, (3) Market. Do subscription journals fit into these domains?<br />Ad 1. Quality. Yes. The Journal Score Card is business model neutral.<br />Ad 2. Open Access. No. Subscription is at odds with Open Access.<br />Ad 3. Market. No. The current Big Deal packages obscure any market idea.<br />So, subscription journals do not fit in QOAM. Yet, the initiators of QOAM are convinced that quality control as such is equally well necessary for subscription journals. Especially for new journals which are simply included in existing packages. The Journal Score Card, or an adapted version of it, might be applicable here and the initiators of QOAM are open to discuss this.</p>
            
