            <h3 id="no-metrics">Why does QOAM not include metrics as a quality proxy?</h3>
            <p>Metrics for QOAM must apply to young journals because most  journals which are born OA are in their infancy. Therefore, the Journal Impact Factor is not included. The Leiden institute CWTS developed an Editorial Board Indicator, a metric for the scientific impact of the editorial board. The main obstacle for applying it is the problem of identifying the board members; just a name and an affiliation are not enough for that. The importance of having a clear identification of the Editorial Board members of scientific journals (i.e. their full names, affiliations, e-mail and even their ORCID identifier) can be also considered as an element of transparency and quality. Should these data be more transparent and accessible, indicators on the scientific impact of the editorial board could then be extensively developed and included in QOAM. See <a href="http://www.surf.nl/en/publicaties/Pages/CWTSrapport.aspx">SURF</a>. Other straightforward young journal metrics would be welcomed by QOAM as well.</p>

            <h3 id="framing">Is QOAM prone to improper use?</h3>
            @Html.Raw(string.Format("<p>To avoid unqualified contributions to QOAM, only members of the academic community may publish Journal Score Cards. Membership will be controlled by federated authentication via trusted third parties like SURFconext in the Netherlands. Per person only one JSC may be published for a specific journal. Published Journal Score Cards are non-anonymous. Their authors can be contacted by other members of the academic community via the <a href=\"{0}\" title=\"Profiles section\">Profiles section</a> of QOAM.<br/>                Currently, QOAM has no resources to organise any form of social control or moderation. We have to rely on academic vigilance. Jeffrey Beall’s <a href=\"http://scholarlyoa.com/individual-journals/\" title=\"list of predatory journals\">list of predatory journals</a> and John Bohannon’s article <a href=\"http://www.sciencemag.org/content/342/6154/60.full\" title=\"Who is Afraid of Peer Review?\">Who is Afraid of Peer Review?</a> are examples of this.</p>", Url.Action("Index", "Profiles")))

            <h3 id="connect-institute">How to get my institute connected to QOAM’s scoring section?</h3>
            <p>QOAM is a fully open web site but only academic staff may publish Journal Score Cards in QOAM. To avoid unauthorized publishing of such cards QOAM has been registered with eduGAIN. EduGAIN interconnects identity federations around the world, simplifying access to content, services and resources for the global research and education community. This will enable staff of your institute to simply log in to the scoring section of QOAM via their institutional account. <br/>To effectuate this your institute has to be registered as a QOAM participant. A registration request can be sent to Leo Waaijers, using the Contact option behind the ‘Learn more’ button in QOAM.  Don’t forget to include the name of your internet domain in this mail. The domain is the extension of your email address behind the @@ sign. If you feel uncertain about the domain name of your institute please contact your ICT department. <br/>The registration will be confirmed by SURFconext, the Dutch eduGAIN partner. Please be aware that the procedure may take about a week. Once your institute is registered in QOAM, staff have access via their institutional account and may start publishing Journal Score Cards in QOAM.</p>
